commentBody:
@John Ezra —

Your mention yesterday of Franz Hals in a comment yesterday reminded me of what must be the first record of a selfie in progress:

<a href="https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/436616" target="_blank">https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/436616</a>

@Francis
@Andrzej

Maybe I'm a masochist. I enjoy thinking about days gone by and activities that will never happen again. Sure, I *could* jump on the furniture, but how fun would that be with no one to do it with me?

If I had kids, I'd not only let them play THE FLOOR IS LAVA, I'd probably teach it to them. Just one of many reasons why it's probably best that I didn't have kids!

@Teresa

I doubt the constructor, the editors and all the test solvers "didn't catch it".  Instead, I think it is an intentional pun, playing off the idea that "the long haul" is a set phrase, and also that the halls in some buildings (think large schools and hospitals, the Pentagon, etc.) are literally very long.

HAUL as the answer to [Long way to go?] wouldn't sit well with me.

@dutchiris

That's such a great painting. I love glimpses into the real world of the past. Posed formal portraits are interesting, sure, but they don't give you the same feel for the times as this. There is an element of human connection here, both between the subjects and between them and me. Fascianting.

Thank you!

@Mike

You have been missed!

Several people have ashed about you.

@Mike

Coincidentally, "Mount Lewotobi Laki Laki erupted at 5:35pm local time today, unleashing a 6.8-mile (11-kilometer) hot ash column over the tourist island of Flores in south-central Indonesia."  

 That blew me away.

@Stephen

Yeah, sure, there's a really large potential for a natick there.

Of course the question is, and always will be, will it be naticky to everyone?  Some people?  No one?

@Steven M.

I know from past postings that some of us sometimes annoy you with responses to comments like this.  Believe me, we, too, are annoyed by a lot of posts.

But the fact is I *like* hearing what the better solvers think.  After all, they're better.  Maybe I can get better.

@Bruce

Lecture appreciated.  If people my age need to learn and remember relatively well-known rap artists, then younger folks can keep Eudora Welty handy.  She is not obscure at all.

Also, TGel is a good shampoo.  I used to use it a lot, so neither of these entries was remotely Natick-y for me.

@Stephen

I looked up both. As a reasonably well-read Polish guy WELTY I've never seen before (of the authors mentioned in the lecture above I've heard of Harper Lee, and I tried reading Faulkner in high school, but was quickly and utterly defeated by the stream of consciousness style), and even though now I recall seeing TGEL here before, I don't even try to remember US brand and product names, because it's completely pointless for European me.

A Natick if there ever was one, since at least WELbY is as viable as Welty, and an American product can be named anything.

@Steven M.

Yes, it can.  It definitely can.  The thing is, it's pretty hard to be *sure* it is.

If you're like me, if I'm having a good day, I give the benefit of the doubt.  But on a bad day....

@Stephen
Agree this is an example of a Natick, but it was one I happened to know fairly easily. 
The SW corner for me….that was another story. Two movie references crossed with a proper name - also a Natick.

@Stephen
I'll just add that EUDORA is seen in puzzles every once in awhile (with the clue being something like "Author Welty").  It's a good name to learn.  "The Optimist's Daughter", the book that won her the Pulitzer, really is a great book!

I didn't know TGEL, but now I'm happy to know it for the future (my future entails being an ironically-named rap star (I'm bald)).

@Steven M.

I have plenty of examples of things that are "personal naticks..." for instance, any athlete beyond those that are absolute household names, current pop stars, and internet influencers.

But I wouldn't catahorize being stopped by two of any of those crossing as a "textbook definition of a natick." It's just my own ignorance in those areas. If I used that phrase, it would be to describe a crossing of two proper that most people, not just me, would find extremely obscure.

@Barry Ancona

Oh, for sure. And I generally don't criticize vocab clues because I don't think not knowing a five dollar word is a reason for me to criticize a word puzzle. Or word play/misdirects the result in an aha moment when finally revealed. Long HALL would be a rare exception to that, and I think most commentators agree on that one.

My gripe is and always has been with trivia crossing trivia. Because at that point it's a memory game, not a puzzle. Note that I would have the same complaint if a crossing was the fifth letter of "2022 Wimbledon Champion" and the first letter of "Run measured in Parsecs." Both easy gimmes for me, but a lot of people would cry Natick, and I'd agree with them.

@Cat Lady Margaret

In denying that the ceiling fixture was your doing, perhaps you were playing a variant of the game, called Blind Man's Bluff!

Those super balls sure could bounce!

@sotto voce
As Francis said. Aka The Concorde. I had TWA first, also.

My sister and I used to play a game called Timber on my double bed. We'd jump up and down a bunch of times, yell timber, then fall backwards.  And that, boys and girls, is how my nose gotten broken when the back of her head hit the front of mine. And my mother was not thrilled with all the blood on the white bedspread, either.

@Francis 

Thank you!

@Vaer

Aaah, the Concorde, what a beauty it was. My father took us to the airport to watch it land once. I was only about six, but I'll never forget it. Later on, I came to think that by now we would all be flying only Concordes everywhere, in magnificent speed and comfort. Ha! Well, that kind of went sideways, didn't it?

Timber, eh? Ouch! Let me guess...and the last time you ever played Timber was...

@Heidi

My mother would have killed us if we had attempted to play that in our house.  We weren't even allowed in the living room except when there was company.

(I was about 21 before I realized that "living room" wasn't an ironic name.)

@Steve L

That's good info, thanks!

You've reminded me of that book written by two flight attendants when they were still called stewardesses, "Coffee, Tea, or Me?" Remember that?

@Beth in Greenbelt

You'll also se ATOZ as an answer from time to time (105 total appearances).

With 28 appearances, ATOB is a relative rarity.

@rajeevfromca

You say "lectured", I say "explained" or "taught".

That's how you learn to understand the clues and gain skill.

@Beth in Greenbelt

A BAR CRAWL involves going from bar to bar and getting wasted, hence the crawl. I did it once, at my BFFs stag party in Amsterdam, and I still hate myself for it.

(It is also possible you were joking about this and the humor was lost on me. With English being my second language, I'm sometimes as clueless about subtle humor as Mr Data)

@dutchiris

It's HALL thought, not HAuL... I see in other comments people are generally confused by the entry, thinking it's just not very good, and simply about some halls being long 🤷

@Francis

My father (who sits on the local council) stopped mowing his lawn last year. His garden is full of wild flowers now, a veritable meadow, a heaven and haven for insects and birds. It looks good, and thousands of creatures benefit from it. 

Also, the city of Warsaw is constantly replacing lawns with trees, shrubs, and meadows, and what lawns remain are only mowed three times a year, to reduce environmental impact. The city recommends housing estates refrain from mowing their lawns, and watering them, too.

@N.E. Body 

If it's just a HALL, why the question mark in the clue implying wordplay?

@Steve L

Sure, but it sounds the same, and in fact it *is* the same name, just spelled alternately.

@Andrzej

I read it as: Long way to go, as in having to go to the bathroom. 

A hall might be a long way to go (if you have to go really bad).

@Andrzej
@Francis

A neighbor has quit mowing a large swath of their lot and put up a "Pardon the weeds, we're feeding the bees" sign. I love it, but the husband is still a traditional lawn guy. 🙄

@Steve L

It happened A LOT when I was growing up. I'll never forget TPing the house of a boy my friends and I liked with 60 rolls. (We counted!) He was mad at us the next day (someone must have blabbed) because his parents made him clean it up. 

My sister once TPed our own house because she had this idea that only popular kids' houses got that treatment, and she wanted people to think we were popular. But she foiled her own plan by only TPing the backyard where no one else could see it.  Adolescent brains are so interesting.

@James W

I did not understand it, either. I also could not think of any etymology for card as wit, so I looked it up:

<a href="https://english.stackexchange.com/questions/151915/etymology-of-card-referring-to-an-eccentric-person" target="_blank">https://english.stackexchange.com/questions/151915/etymology-of-card-referring-to-an-eccentric-person</a>

@Vaer
I, too, remember playing "Quicksand" as a child, but I think we also played "Hot lava" (as we called it) as well. We also played it outdoors, on a swing set/jungle gym.

Our homestead was a very dangerous place!

@Vaer
Ah, car trips in my cousins' old woody station wagon--my cousin and I sitting backwards in the bed of the rear. 

And yet we survived.

@Francis

Yes, classic sampling error.
Like all those struggling swimmers who've been saved when dolphins nudged them towards the shore? Maybe we just don't here from the people the dolphins nudged out to sea...

@Oikofuge

In the end, I simply decided that a HALL is an (indoor) way that is often long.

I still hope there's a better connection between the clue and answer.

@Peter
Exactly the pairs that I had to look up as well! I did understand TPED ("toilet papered") after seeing the answer and remembering old South Park episodes... But during the solve it wouldn't come to me.
Good puzzle!

@JohnWM
Yeah right. You got the B-52s as an earworm--all I got was Hall and Oates:
<a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ccenFp_3kq8&list=RDccenFp_3kq8&start_radio=1" target="_blank">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ccenFp_3kq8&list=RDccenFp_3kq8&start_radio=1</a>

@Lewis

the only alternatives I came up with are NSFW and not safe for children's play --- lap dancing and couch bonking.

But then I'd never played the game, and only heard of it a few years ago. Sounds like living room parkour. My parents would not allow us to jump or stand on the furniture.

@deeb
Apparently, it's an old children's game that (much later) became a meme.
Both are news to me.

@Xword Junkie

T-GEL and T-Sal have both been in the puzzle in the past few months. Useful letters for crossword construction.

I remember a discussion of T-GEL because it's been discontinued by Neutrogena, but Walgreens still carries their store brand version. T-GEL has coal tar in it, which California decided required labeling as a possible carcinogen

@Xword Junkie
Eudora WELTY's home and garden are a Point of Interest in Jackson.  Someone lent me her book of Welty's short stories, which I ...can't recommend.  I could never get very far with her most well-known novel, _Delta Wedding_.  Perhaps she just belonged to an earlier time that I am unable to appreciate or relate to?  

Old TV shows would be just as hard for solvers...Mucous WELBY would be unworthy of exhumation, IMHO.

@Rich
I'd say those are pretty tame compared to, say, "No tickee, no washee."

Seriously, Chinese tend to de-emphasize the self in favor of the collective, so it's common to omit the first person pronoun. I don't know if that's a feature of Communism, or if it goes back to Confucianism.

@Steve L

As someone fluent in Tok Pisin and an amateur linguist, I appreciate you raising this information.  

Knowing that you like to have the details correct, I must add that Tok Pisin is spoken only in the country of Papua New Guinea.   The term New Guinea applies to the entire island, which is shared with Indonesia.

@Joe
Our family use it at all times and all occasions. One does not simply walk into Mordor on a whim. 
I get extra points for mimicking Sean Bean’s Yorkshire accent (tis mine own birthright too)

@Hanson

Your comment reminds me that we haven't heard from Eddie in Kentucky for quite a while, who used to tell us when he "done did this puzz."

I didn't think that I would be among those who miss him.

