@Gail F
Thanks!
I was still wondering what the? about that one.

@Bill
I had TWA...then SWA...then all that was MIA when
I remembered the old standby SST.

@Grant
And a good thing too! it was bad enough with Ronald Reagan National Airport. Code is still DCA. (and I think the city made Congress pay for changing all the Metro signs which used to just be National Airport.)
Isn't Chicago's O'hare still ORD  from the Orchard days?

@Grant who posted: "Jimmies on the west coast, sprinkles in the east. That's been my experience, anyway."

I think you have that one backwards. I spent half my childhood years in the Boston area, where they were definitely called "jimmies," not "sprinkles" as in most other places outside the Northeast. And the Wikipedia article agrees:
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sprinkles" target="_blank">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sprinkles</a>

@Mu
If any given day's puzzles start seeming too easy (Mondays usually are for me), the either skip or find a way to make them harder like only downs or only acrosses.
Though it seems odd to complain about too easy and too much arcana in the same post.

@Cindy I thought of "long way to go" as in long-haul trucking, and it seemed straightforward. It was the question mark that clued me to think differently.

Having ridden cross country in a couple of those long haul trucks, let me tell you, you'll realize round about the middle of Texas that you still have a very long way to go to get to the Santa Monica pier. 

I do tend to think of HALLs as longer than they are wide, but for me, getting that from "long way to go" required reinterpreting that common phrase in a more literal sense. But YMMV.
